<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Allan Ulrich 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DONIZETTI: "ANNA BOLENA." Joan Sutherland, Susanne Mentzer, Jerry Hadley, 
Samuel Ramey; Chorus and Orchestra of Welsh National Opera conducted by Richard 
Bonynge. London 421-096-2 (three compact discs). Sutherland is a fit tragic 
heroine for Donizetti's inventive dip into bel-canto Elizabethiana. The 
Australian soprano still commands an authority that few of her contemporaries 
can match -- the extended finale before the beheading is still worth waiting 
for -- but the occasional underpitch note and unraveled phrase suggests this 
project should have been done a decade ago. Sutherland's unfailingly youthful 
colleagues underline her current vocal estate. American mezzo Mentzer brings 
fresh tone and a persistent vibrato to Jane Seymour. Hadley proclaims Percy's 
ardent sentiments with cultivated tenorial fervor. Ramey is an orotund and 
sympathetic Henry VIII. Bonynge accommodates them all, without imposing much 
personality on the project. Allan Ulrich 
</P>
</TEXT>
