<HEADLINE>
<P>
GASTRIC BALLOON CURBS THE APPETITE; 
</P>
<P>
RATIONALE IS THAT THE PATIENT WILL FEEL FULL, EAT LESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I was interested in reading in your column about the use of a balloon 
that goes into a person's stomach so that he doesn't feel like eating so much. 
What I don't quite understand is how the balloon gets into the stomach. How big 
is it? Am I right in assuming that it cannot be swallowed? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: The gastric balloon is placed in the patient's stomach through a 
narrow, flexible tube that passes down the throat and the esophagus. The 
balloon is deflated when inserted, and then blown up to about the size of a 
grapefruit. The entire procedure can be accomplished within a few minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Use of the gastric balloon avoids the need for surgery. The rationale behind 
its use is that the person will feel full and therefore tend to eat less. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I had always been under the impression that syphilis was a curable disease, 
but I saw some figures recently about the number of cases that are found each 
year. If syphilis is curable, why should so many people be getting it? It would 
seem to me that it would have been wiped out by now. 
</P>
<P>
A: Penicillin can cure all stages of syphilis, but not unless the patient makes 
himself or herself available for treatment. The later a person is treated, the 
larger the dose that will be needed and the longer the duration of treatment. 
Those who are allergic to penicillin may be treated with tetracycline or 
erythromycin; however, tetracycline should not be used by pregnant women 
because it causes permanent discoloration of the baby's teeth. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Does myocardial infarction and heart attack mean the same thing? I have even 
heard both expressions used in the same sentence, so I'm beginning to think 
that they are actually the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
A: Myocardial infarction is the medical term for heart attack. "Myocardial" 
refers to the heart muscle, and "infarction" refers to tissue death. Other 
terms used to refer to a heart attack are coronary occlusion, coronary 
thrombosis, or just plain coronary. In general, they all mean the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
Q: If a man has an ostomy will that make him impotent? I know there are some 
operations that do have this effect. 
</P>
<P>
A: Ostomy surgery may cause impotence or sterility in some patients, but this 
does not occur in all cases. In one study of more than 300 patients, 12% 
reported that they experienced such problems. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I am a teacher and occasionally there is a child in one of my classes who is 
on insulin. I would appreciate some information about the symptoms of an 
insulin reaction. How may I recognize one? I would like to be prepared. 
</P>
<P>
A: The early symptoms of an insulin reaction include hunger, sweating, 
irritability, headache, an increased pulse rate and increased blood pressure. 
Later, the patient may show confusion and bizarre behavior. And, still later, 
convulsions and coma may occur. 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. Neil Solomon is a specialist in endocrinology and metabolism and an 
authority on obesity. He also holds a doctorate in psychology. Questions may be 
sent to him at P.O. Box 21487, Pikesville, Md. 21208. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
