<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEARNING TO COPE WITH TOO MANY CHOICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There were scary stories in the Sunday paper: "911 System Crashes," "Medicare 
Costs Rising," "Jerry Brown Returns to California Politics." Scariest of all 
was "Overchoice . . . Experts . . . Wonder . . . If 57 Varieties . . . Too Much 
of a Good Thing." 
</P>
<P>
Only in America would such a complaint be printed in a major newspaper. The 
gist of the polemic was that the marvelous abundance of goods produced by 
capitalism causes consumer stress and anxiety. The implied conclusion: These 
dumb bunnies need to be protected for their own good from greedy, manipulative 
marketers. 
</P>
<P>
Who are the protectors? Why, experts! Experts like the psychologist/attorney 
who sells relief from such terrible stress. Experts like author Jeremy Rifkin, 
who now ventures into pop psychology to tell us that people are really 
emotionally stressed over product choices. What Rifkin is selling is control 
over people's lives. He wants rules. And he wants to be the rule-maker. 
</P>
<P>
It's the rule-maker's never ending refrain: People are too stupid, apathetic, 
irresponsible, to be free. They cannot possibly enjoy America's abundance. . . 
. 
</P>
<P>
It's ironic that as country after country turns away from rules and regulations 
and toward free-market capitalism, aspiring rule makers work ever harder here 
at home. The marketplace will cure "overchoice," if it exists, by bankrupting 
products and companies which do not provide value. 
</P>
<P>
BEN M. ENIS 
</P>
<P>
Professor of Marketing 
</P>
</TEXT>
