<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAKING TURNS IN CLASS; 
</P>
<P>
HALF A JOB IS PERFECT ASSIGNMENT FOR TEACHERS WILLING TO SHARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICIA WARD BIEDERMAN, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gregg, who is 5, runs up to his kindergarten teacher with a question. "Mrs. 
Carley," he says, then quickly corrects himself, "I mean, Mrs. Snyder." 
</P>
<P>
Gregg's momentary confusion is understandable. On Mondays, Tuesdays and 
alternate Wednesdays, Gregg's teacher at Madison Elementary School in Lakewood 
is Shiela Carley. On Thursdays, Fridays and the remaining Wednesdays, Donna 
Snyder readies Gregg and his classmates for reading and cheers them on as they 
count and finger-paint. 
</P>
<P>
Carley and Snyder share a desk, a classroom and a single job. While job sharing 
has not swept American schools, it appeals to a minority of teachers who can 
afford to trade part of a salary for more time to raise children, take college 
courses or ease into retirement. 
</P>
<P>
No figures are available on how many teachers job-share nationwide. Statewide 
statistics have not been updated since 1981 when a survey of California's 1,042 
school districts found that 37% had tried job sharing and that more than 1,500 
California teachers were sharing jobs. 
</P>
<P>
According to Suzanne Smith, who conducted the 1981 survey, a recent informal 
canvass indicates that the number of districts that allow the practice has 
grown, although she does not know whether the number of job sharers has 
increased. (Smith is co-founder and co-director of the nonprofit organization 
New Ways to Work in San Francisco.) Most of the job-sharing teachers are women 
with young children, although pairs have included men, married couples and even 
a mother-daughter team. 
</P>
<P>
Of the Long Beach Unified School District's 3,300 teachers, 34, including 
Carley and Snyder, share jobs. Los Angeles Unified School District has about 
200 job-sharers among its 33,000 teachers. The National Education Assn. gave 
the practice a boost by endorsing it in 1981. Many unions, including United 
Teachers-Los Angeles, which represents Los Angeles Unified teachers, support 
the concept of job sharing. 
</P>
<P>
Even without union pressure, most local school districts allow the practice, at 
the discretion of individual principals. Culver City Unified School District, 
for example, permits job sharing, although it has had no requests for several 
years. Beverly Hills Unified School District recently approved job sharing for 
an initial pair of teachers. 
</P>
<P>
Job sharing increases a school district's paper work, but most administrators 
feel it is worth the price. Richard Marr, an official with the Montebello 
Unified School District, said job sharing, or tandem teaching, as the district 
calls it, "seems to have worked quite well." It is one way the district can 
retain good teachers who might otherwise leave the profession, he said. The 
district has five teams, most of them teaching mothers, among its 1,300 
teachers. "What we usually find," Marr said, "is that after their families 
mature they come back to full-time teaching." 
</P>
<P>
Carley and Snyder have shared their Lakewood classroom for three years. Both 
have toddlers at home and see the arrangement as a way to eliminate the guilty 
sense many working mothers have that they are not doing their best on either 
front. As Snyder said, "When I'm at work, I want to give 100% to my job, and 
when I'm with my family, I want to give 100% to them, and this allows me to do 
that." As a result of job sharing, Carley said, "I'm completing housework 
before 11 o'clock at night." 
</P>
<P>
Carley and Snyder, who were friends before they were partners, say their 
students have little or no trouble adjusting to two teachers instead of one. As 
they point out, many of the youngsters attended preschools where they had more 
than one teacher. And both teachers are in the classroom each day during the 
first week of school so the children get to know both of them at the beginning 
of the school year. 
</P>
<P>
Interviewed in a schoolyard sandbox, several of the youngsters stopped playing 
long enough to say yes when asked if they liked having two teachers. Parent 
Joan Wagner, whose 6-year-old son, Scott, is in the class, said "it's nice for 
the children to have a change." Carley and Snyder's principal, James Churchill, 
is also pleased with the arrangement. Each of the pair gives more than 50% of 
her time and energy to the school, Churchill said. 
</P>
<P>
Compatibility and good communication are the keys to making the arrangement 
work, according to job-sharing teachers Jill Cooper and Mary Schachner. 
Schachner and Cooper have been teaching a combined first and second grade at 
Larch Avenue Elementary School in Lennox for six years. Both were pregnant when 
they proposed to their principal that they share the job. They were one of 
Lennox School District's three pioneering pairs. The district now has eight job 
sharers among its 200 teachers. 
</P>
<P>
Cooper, who is bilingual, teaches Spanish reading and other courses in the 
mornings, while Schachner, who teaches in English, takes over in the 
afternoons. To keep abreast of what is happening in class, the women often 
lunch together. "And we leave notes for each other on our desk," Schachner 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Carley and Snyder also leave messages on their mutual desk. They keep a single 
classroom log as well, noting which child can't seem to concentrate, who wet 
his or her pants, who is having trouble with the s sound and anything else that 
might affect student performance. They also call each other regularly, usually 
waiting until their own children are in bed. 
</P>
<P>
Smith, the survey taker, said the most innovative mode of communication she 
found among job-sharing teachers involved a pair who lived close to each other 
but had a substantial commute to their school. After her shift, one teacher 
would tape-record her observations about the class. She then dropped the tape 
in her partner's mailbox so the partner could listen to it the next morning as 
she drove to school. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Husband-Wife Team 
</P>
<P>
Communication was not a problem for former job-sharers Dian and Harold 
Stonbraker. The Stonbrakers were on the Artesia High School faculty when Dian 
became pregnant with their son, Sean, now 6. Both wanted to stay home with 
their first child. They arranged to share Dian's job, teaching home economics 
for a semester on alternate days (a substitute was hired to teach Harold's 
social studies classes). "When it was her day to work, I got up at night to 
feed Sean and change his diaper," he recalled. Some of Harold's fondest 
memories are of the hours he was able to spend caring for his newborn son, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
On rare occasions, Harold recalled, their shared students would try to divide 
and conquer the teaching pair -- with little success. "The kids would try to 
pull things. They would say, 'Mrs. Stonbraker said. . . .' They forgot I went 
home every day and saw Mrs. Stonbraker." 
</P>
<P>
The Stonbrakers are now back in separate classrooms at Artesia. The ABC Unified 
School District has three pairs among its 900 teachers, including teams who 
share library and physical education slots. 
</P>
<P>
Most job-sharers sign contracts that specify how they will divide the work and 
commit the survivor to taking over the class if one of them decides to drop 
out. Most districts split salary and benefits between the teachers on the basis 
of their division of classroom responsibility, although Palos Verdes Peninsula 
Unified School District pays full benefits to each of its 16 job-sharing 
teachers. 
</P>
<P>
Although most job-sharers say the arrangement has improved the quality of their 
lives, they cite other benefits as well. Snyder said she arrives at school on 
Wednesday or Thursday refreshed and eager to teach -- it is the beginning of 
the work week for her -- just when a teacher who is going it alone may be 
starting to flag. She and her partner are rarely sick, and when one is, the 
other substitutes. 
</P>
<P>
Carley said the setup lessens the likelihood of burnout and helps her cope with 
the occasional "children who would wear you down if you had them for a week. I 
have a lot more tolerance and energy to give them." The pair also says the 
children benefit from having two people plan their academic program. "Because 
there are two of us, there's more going on," Carley said. "It's more exciting. 
There are more ideas." 
</P>
<P>
Schachner said dividing responsibilities has allowed her and partner Cooper to 
become specialists in the subjects they teach. "I think I've become a better 
teacher because I don't have to spread myself so thin." 
</P>
<P>
Although Carley sometimes misses a full paycheck, she notes that she saves on 
everything from commuting costs to a professional wardrobe. "I don't have to 
worry about wearing the same black skirt five days in a row," she said. More 
important, job sharing means she can do both the things she wants to do most: 
teach and be with her family. As fellow job-sharer Cooper said, she works at 
her teaching job more than half time "but I don't mind. It's the best of both 
worlds." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, As Donna Snyder teaches shared kindergarten class, partner teacher 
Shiela Carley peeks in door to see how things are going. ; Photo, Shiela Carley 
chooses among the raised hands of kindergartners for a response to her question 
at Madison School in Lakewood. EUGENE TANNER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
