<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
California 120 leading into Yosemite Valley has been reopened after being 
closed 2 1/2 days by a rock slide. A 60-yard section of the road was clogged by 
huge rocks in a slide park officials blamed on the alternate freezing and 
thawing of recent weeks. Even though five boulders as large as automobiles 
crashed down the mountain onto the pavement, no injuries were reported. Two 
other major routes to Yosemite, California 41 and 140, remained open. 
California 120, which enters the park from the Modesto area via Tuolumne 
County, reopened Friday just in time for throngs heading to Yosemite for the 
three-day President's Day weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
