<HEADLINE>
<P>
LATINO: VAGUE DEFINITION CAN RAISE QUESTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM SCHACHTER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Because the definition of the term Latino is vague, experts say minority 
contracting programs are rife with vendors whose status as Latinos is 
debatable. 
</P>
<P>
GTE California, for example, is reviewing the status of Doty Brothers Equipment 
Co. in Norwalk, which did $2.2 million in heavy construction work for the 
utility last year. 
</P>
<P>
The company has qualified as Latino-owned at several utilities and government 
agencies, President John T. Doty said, because his grandfather was born in 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
Asked if he considered himself Hispanic, Doty acknowledged that he is "kind of 
ambivalent" about the issue. 
</P>
<P>
"In thinking about the question, I can't give an answer," he said. "The only 
racial slurs ever thrown at me have been in Mexico, where I've been called a 
gringo." 
</P>
<P>
But Doty said he does not believe that he has taken advantage of the utilities' 
minority contracting programs, because he gets work only when he offers the 
best price. 
</P>
<P>
"In my experience in construction, it's the bottom line," he said. "It's 
whatever we bid." JIM SCHACHTER 
</P>
</TEXT>
