<HEADLINE>
<P>
GRAMMY WEEK REPORT; 
</P>
<P>
THE PASSAGES OF ROCK; 
</P>
<P>
WHY LOS ANGELES IS COURTING THE GRAMMYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles city officials -- stung last year by the Grammy Awards ceremony 
being held in New York City after six years at L.A.'s Shrine Auditorium -- are 
going all out to keep the awards here permanently. 
</P>
<P>
James Stewart, executive director of the Los Angeles Host Committee for the 
1989 Grammy Awards, said the city has raised approximately $200,000 through 
private donations to sponsor a series of activities saluting the return of the 
Grammys to the Shrine on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
Efforts have included placing of "Los Angeles Welcomes the Grammy Awards" 
banners around town, a half-day "Grammys in the Schools" program held last 
Friday, a three-concert jazz "Night on the Town," also last Friday, and a 
reception to be hosted by Mayor Tom Bradley on Monday night for Grammy 
officials at the new Gene Autry Heritage Museum. 
</P>
<P>
Six hundred officers and members of the Grammy-sponsoring National Academy of 
Recording Arts and Sciences are expected to attend the mayor's reception. 
</P>
<P>
"(Keeping the Grammys in L.A.) is the No. 1 result we're after," said Stewart 
(no relation to the actor). The awards show has been held in Los Angeles all 
but five years since the Grammys were initiated in 1959. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Greene, president of the National Academy of Recording Arts and 
Sciences, sponsors of the Grammys, said no decision has been made about the 
site of next year's event, but did acknowledge that New York members of the 
academy are "hopeful of getting it back." 
</P>
<P>
Though the city benefits from the business generated by the estimated 3,000 
people who will come to town for the Grammy ceremonies, Host Committee chairman 
Sheldon I. Ausman said his committee is motivated by more than the money the 
awards generate. 
</P>
<P>
"Our view of this is on a much higher plane," said Ausman, who is chairman of 
the board of KCET. Noting that the committee is part of a broader Mayor's Blue 
Ribbon Committee for the Entertainment Industry, he added, "The Grammys and the 
Academy Awards and the Emmys represent Los Angeles as the home of the 
entertainment industry, and we would like to keep all three shows here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
GRAMMY AWARDS; NATIONAL ACADEMY OF RECORDING ARTS AND SCIENCES; LOS ANGELES -- 
CULTURE; RECORDING INDUSTRY; ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY; MUSIC; AWARDS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021989-0218 </DOCNO>
