<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEEPING A SECRET; 
</P>
<P>
ROCKWELL'S NEW 'STAR WARS' FACILITY IN SEAL BEACH IS DESIGNED TO FOIL SPIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID OLMOS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Inside Building No. 90, a portable radio blares rock music as construction 
workers put the finishing touches on the most secretive defense plant ever 
built by Rockwell International Corp. 
</P>
<P>
The sound of Bob Seger seems somehow incongruous with the serious purpose of 
this $30-million structure: the development of top-secret plans for the "Star 
Wars" missile-defense program. 
</P>
<P>
The nearly completed four-story structure at Rockwell's Seal Beach facility is 
the centerpiece of the company's effort to land lucrative "Star Wars" 
contracts. Called the Strategic Defense Center, it is also part of an ambitious 
corporate experiment aimed at finding a better way to manage large, complex 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
Although the future of the controversial "Star Wars" program is far from 
certain, Rockwell is convinced that its investment in the Strategic Defense 
Center will be money well spent. 
</P>
<P>
Rockwell executives believe that in one form or another, "Star Wars" technology 
will be around for a long time. Like earlier space programs, they said, the 
research effort is expected to serve as the engine for many new technological 
breakthroughs with applications for other projects at the $12-billion aerospace 
and defense firm. 
</P>
<P>
Rockwell has assembled at the center a group consisting of hundreds of top 
engineers, scientists and computer experts -- many of whom were teamed together 
on the Apollo space program 2 decades ago. About 1,000 people will work at the 
center when it is fully staffed. 
</P>
<P>
The personnel assigned to the center will come mostly from Rockwell's other 
divisions throughout Southern California, where the company employs 35,000 
people. 
</P>
<P>
They will work inside a mostly windowless facility with an array of security 
precautions reminiscent of scenes from a spy thriller. 
</P>
<P>
The building is a bewildering maze of stark hallways, soundproof rooms and 
offices protected by high-security locks, infrared sensors and double layers of 
doors. In the most sensitive areas, offices are protected by huge steel doors 
like those used in bank vaults. 
</P>
<P>
The floor, ceiling and walls are extra-thick and loaded with special materials 
to prevent radio or computer transmissions from escaping outside, where they 
might be intercepted by spies using sophisticated electronic equipment. 
</P>
<P>
Air-conditioning ducts have been sealed off to prevent intruders from crawling 
their way into trouble. And telephone lines have been secured. 
</P>
<P>
Nothing, it seems, has been taken for granted. Even a simple thing like 
reminding employees to close a door behind them warrants a sign reading: 
"Please verify door is closed. For door problems, please call immediately." 
Construction workers had to undergo security checks to ensure they didn't plant 
eavesdropping devices in the building. That precaution was taken to prevent a 
replay of what happened at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow. Last year, former 
President Reagan ordered the partially completed embassy torn down and 
reconstructed because the building's Soviet-made concrete casings were found to 
be riddled with listening devices. 
</P>
<P>
Access to some areas of the Rockwell facility is so difficult that center 
director George W. Jeffs, even with the use of a map, had difficulty locating 
the "battle management" program offices during a recent tour with a Times 
reporter. 
</P>
<P>
The battle management program involves the development of computer systems to 
manage a "Star Wars" system. The battle management area includes large computer 
displays in which a "Star Wars" scenario could be simulated. 
</P>
<P>
The center's main purpose will be to oversee Rockwell's work on the "Star Wars" 
program, formally known as the Strategic Defense Initiative. 
</P>
<P>
El Segundo-based Rockwell was the nation's fourth-largest SDI contractor in 
1988 and has current contracts totaling $778 million. 
</P>
<P>
"Star Wars" is a proposed space-based, anti-missile system designed to act as 
both a shield and deterrent to a Soviet nuclear attack. Viewed by supporters as 
a strategic necessity and by critics as the ultimate boondoggle, billions of 
research dollars have been poured into the program during the past 6 years. 
Some of the program's prototype systems are beginning to undergo tests, but a 
decision about deployment is years away. 
</P>
<P>
A number of Orange County defense contractors are getting a piece of the "Star 
Wars" action, including McDonnell Douglas Corp. in Huntington Beach, Hughes 
Aircraft Co. in Fullerton and Interstate Electronics Corp. in Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
Rockwell is a prime contractor on one of the centerpiece projects for "Star 
Wars," the Space-Based Interceptor program. That project involves a satellite 
designed to fire high-energy projectiles known as "smart rocks" at ballistic 
missiles, destroying them by the speed and force of impact. The company's other 
programs include electronic sensors, high-energy lasers and computer systems to 
manage a "Star Wars" battle. 
</P>
<P>
The Space-Based Interceptor program was threatened last year after the Defense 
Acquisition Board issued an unfavorable review of the program, saying it would 
cost too much. However, recent changes in the design of the program have 
lowered its proposed costs from $52 billion to $17.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
Rockwell's investment in the new facility, which is expected to grow to $50 
million over the next few years, is "a practical effort to help us marshal our 
resources from throughout the corporation," said Jeffs, the center's director 
and Rockwell's executive vice president for strategic defense and technologies. 
</P>
<P>
The center represents "a new adventure in management," said Jeffs, a 42-year 
veteran of Rockwell who headed the company's work on the Apollo, Skylab and 
Space Shuttle programs. The center is unique, he said, because it is Rockwell's 
first attempt to the centralize management of programs involving many different 
divisions. Eight Rockwell units are presently involved in "Star Wars"-related 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
"In the past, we would try to do projects out of a particular division," Jeffs 
said. "But the expertise of any one division might not be the best of fits for 
a given job. We can tailor this organization to better match the requirements 
of some of the new jobs that don't fall naturally within the business structure 
of our existing divisions." 
</P>
<P>
By locating key personnel from various Rockwell units under a single roof, the 
corporation also hopes to foster a team spirit and eliminate problems of 
inter-division rivalries. "Co-locating people tends to totally eliminate the 
parochial self-interest" of any one division, a Rockwell official explained. 
</P>
<P>
The center will perform program management, research, design and engineering 
work for various "Star Wars" systems. But the production of test hardware will 
be done at different Rockwell units, including Seal Beach and Anaheim in Orange 
County. 
</P>
<P>
Unlike other Rockwell operations, the center won't be evaluated on the basis of 
how much it contributes to the corporation's bottom line. It will function as a 
"nonprofit" facility, with all profits gained from programs managed at the 
center being credited to the Rockwell division that performs the bulk of the 
work. 
</P>
<P>
Rockwell is promoting the center as the first of its kind devoted solely to 
"Star Wars" programs. Company executives believe the center's high-security 
features will prove attractive to its security-conscious customers at the 
Pentagon, providing Rockwell with a potential leg up on its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
When the company began construction of the center in May, 1987, plans called 
for a two-story, 100,000-square-foot structure -- half the size of what has 
been built. The building was designed so that two additional floors could be 
added later. 
</P>
<P>
"We very quickly realized the building size wouldn't match our requirements," 
Jeffs said. "We concluded that from an overall point of view, it would be more 
economical to finish the other two stories now rather than add on to it later." 
</P>
<P>
The Seal Beach site was chosen because it is close to several other "Star Wars" 
projects under way at the company's Satellite Systems Division and computer 
center, also in Seal Beach. 
</P>
<P>
Although the center was designed specifically for SDI work, Jeffs said the 
facility could be used for future classified projects if the controversial 
"Star Wars" program encounters political problems in the years ahead. 
</P>
<P>
Jeffs said he believes that the "Star Wars" program "for one reason or another, 
will continue for a long period of time." 
</P>
<P>
"We feel that SDI is a good technology driver, just like the Apollo program 
was," Jeffs said. "It offers the possibility of a number of spinoffs" to other 
military and commercial businesses in which Rockwell is involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The Rockwell strategic defense research building in Seal Beach is a 
bewildering maze of stark hallways, soundproof rooms and offices protected by 
high-security locks, infrared sensors and double layers of doors. ; Photo, 
Rockwell Vice President George Jeffs in the maze-like building. RICK PERRY / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
